Great follow-up — and no, it’s not necessary to use CosmosAsyncClient. You can absolutely use the sync client (CosmosClient) in your Azure Functions project, especially if:

⸻

✅ You Are:
	•	Writing blocking (non-reactive) Java code
	•	Not using Reactor or Mono/Flux style programming
	•	Prefer simple, easier-to-read logic

⸻

🔄 Sync vs Async — Quick Comparison

Feature	CosmosClient (Sync)	CosmosAsyncClient (Async)
Style	Blocking	Reactive / non-blocking
Ease of use	Simple for most use cases ✅	Requires Reactor / reactive programming
Best for	Functions, REST APIs, simple apps ✅	High-throughput streaming or event-based systems
Can be mixed?	Not recommended (pick one)	Not recommended (pick one)


