✅ So If You’re Already Using CosmosClient…

You can use this version of the utility class (sync version):

⸻

🧱 CosmosClientProvider.java (Sync Version)

package com.your.package.cosmos;

import com.azure.cosmos.*;
import java.util.Map;
import java.util.concurrent.ConcurrentHashMap;

/**
 * Thread-safe utility to manage CosmosClient and cached CosmosContainer instances.
 */
public final class CosmosClientProvider {

    private static final CosmosClient COSMOS_CLIENT = new CosmosClientBuilder()
            .endpoint(System.getenv("COSMOS_DB_ENDPOINT"))
            .key(System.getenv("COSMOS_DB_KEY"))
            .consistencyLevel(ConsistencyLevel.EVENTUAL)
            .buildClient();

    private static final Map<String, CosmosContainer> containerCache = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

    private CosmosClientProvider() {}

    /**
     * Lazily loads and caches CosmosContainer references.
     *
     * @param databaseName  Database name
     * @param containerName Container name
     * @return Cached CosmosContainer
     */
    public static CosmosContainer getContainer(String databaseName, String containerName) {
        String key = databaseName + ":" + containerName;
        return containerCache.computeIfAbsent(key, k ->
            COSMOS_CLIENT.getDatabase(databaseName).getContainer(containerName)
        );
    }

    /**
     * Get singleton CosmosClient
     */
    public static CosmosClient getClient() {
        return COSMOS_CLIENT;
    }
}


⸻

✅ Usage (Sync)

CosmosContainer container = CosmosClientProvider.getContainer("myDb", "myContainer");

// Execute a query
CosmosQueryRequestOptions options = new CosmosQueryRequestOptions();
SqlQuerySpec query = new SqlQuerySpec("SELECT * FROM c WHERE c.id = @id")
    .setParameters(List.of(new SqlParameter("@id", "123")));

Iterable<FeedResponse<JsonNode>> results = container.queryItems(query, options, JsonNode.class).iterableByPage();

for (FeedResponse<JsonNode> page : results) {
    page.getResults().forEach(item -> System.out.println(item.toPrettyString()));
}


⸻

✅ Summary
	•	You can and should use CosmosClient if you’re writing non-reactive Azure Function code.
	•	The sync version is easier to manage, integrates cleanly with most Java apps.
	•	You’ll still get full thread safety, reusability, and lazy container caching.

